WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.020 --> 00:00:05.240
BORIS: Today with us
is Dr. Lewis Dartnell.

00:00:05.240 --> 00:00:10.250
His newest book is-- could
I have a copy of the book

00:00:10.250 --> 00:00:13.940
please-- "The Knowledge,
How to Rebuild Our World

00:00:13.940 --> 00:00:17.620
From Scratch."

00:00:17.620 --> 00:00:24.085
So it's like when I was
pitched by the publishers, hey,

00:00:24.085 --> 00:00:26.910
you should have Lewis come
and give a talk at Google.

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:29.244
I was looking at what is
this, "The Knowledge?"

00:00:29.244 --> 00:00:31.160
There's a lot of knowledge
and all that stuff.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:34.665
And then I read a description
which says-- here,

00:00:34.665 --> 00:00:35.540
I'll read it for you.

00:00:35.540 --> 00:00:38.830
So maybe it was an asteroid
impact, a nuclear war,

00:00:38.830 --> 00:00:40.360
or a viral pandemic.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:43.670
Whatever the cause, the world,
as we know it has ended.

00:00:43.670 --> 00:00:47.250
And you and the other
survivors must start again.

00:00:47.250 --> 00:00:49.300
What key knowledge
would you need

00:00:49.300 --> 00:00:51.850
to not only survive in
the immediate aftermath,

00:00:51.850 --> 00:00:55.650
but avert another dark ages
and accelerate the rebooting

00:00:55.650 --> 00:00:57.560
of civilization from scratch?

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:00.800
Which I thought was an excellent
idea for a technology book,

00:01:00.800 --> 00:01:06.350
how to make the history
of technology more fun.

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:09.280
Well, not fun really,
but it presents

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:11.920
the history of technology
in a different way.

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:14.240
And I think a lot of
people actually agree

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:16.330
that the book is a great read.

00:01:16.330 --> 00:01:19.250
So just to quote
from "The Times,"

00:01:19.250 --> 00:01:22.840
"The Knowledge" is a "New
York Times" and "Sunday Times"

00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:25.680
best seller, and was also
awarded "The Times" New

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:29.630
Thinking Book of the Year, or
from "The Wall Street Journal,"

00:01:29.630 --> 00:01:31.250
"The Knowledge" is
a fascinating look

00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:36.260
at the basic principles of the
most important technologies

00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:38.790
undergirding modern society.

00:01:38.790 --> 00:01:43.030
It's a fun read full of optimism
about human ingenuity," which

00:01:43.030 --> 00:01:45.110
is something that I liked.

00:01:45.110 --> 00:01:48.620
"Terrifically engrossing history
of science and technology,"

00:01:48.620 --> 00:01:49.990
"The Guardian."

00:01:49.990 --> 00:01:52.270
"The ultimate
do-it-yourself guide

00:01:52.270 --> 00:01:55.365
to rebooting human
civilization," "Nature."

00:01:55.365 --> 00:01:59.830
So Dr. Lewis Dartnell is a UK
Space Agency research fellow

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:02.100
at the University of Leicester.

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:05.960
So this is a rocket
scientist here.

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:10.729
He also holds an STFC,
Science in Society Fellowship,

00:02:10.729 --> 00:02:13.230
and alongside his
astrobiology research,

00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:16.990
writes regular science articles
in newspapers and magazines.

00:02:16.990 --> 00:02:20.070
He has appeared in TV shows
such as the BBC "Horizon,"

00:02:20.070 --> 00:02:22.950
"Wonders of the Universe,"
and documentaries

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:25.470
on National Geographic,
Discovery, and History

00:02:25.470 --> 00:02:27.480
Channels.

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:31.707
Please join me in welcoming
Lewis Dartnell to Google.

00:02:31.707 --> 00:02:32.790
LEWIS DARTNELL: Thank you.

00:02:32.790 --> 00:02:35.670
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:39.570
Good afternoon everyone,
and thank you all very much

00:02:39.570 --> 00:02:42.180
for coming along to hear me.

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:44.449
My name's Lewis, as
you've just heard,

00:02:44.449 --> 00:02:46.490
and I'm a research fellow
based at the University

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:49.500
of Leicester in the space
research center there.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:52.910
And my day job, what I do
when I'm not running off

00:02:52.910 --> 00:02:56.530
writing books is working
within astrobiology, which

00:02:56.530 --> 00:02:58.450
is a relatively new
field of science,

00:02:58.450 --> 00:03:01.250
all about extending what
we know about the origins

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:03.660
and the survival limits
of life here on earth,

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:06.662
and extending that to
the possibility of life

00:03:06.662 --> 00:03:08.620
on other planets-- in
particular, our next door

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:13.030
neighbor planet, Mars, where I
spend most of my time thinking,

00:03:13.030 --> 00:03:16.030
could terrestrial life tolerate
and survive the conditions

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:17.950
on the surface of Mars?

00:03:17.950 --> 00:03:19.770
Or more importantly,
what tests could we

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:23.220
design to put on a Mars Rover
and send to the Red Planet

00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:25.300
to try to detect
those signs of life,

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:27.700
those so-called biosignatures.

00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:30.430
But something I've been
thinking about a lot more

00:03:30.430 --> 00:03:33.280
over the last two
or three years is

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:37.080
on something completely
and utterly different.

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:40.530
And let's imagine that
this has actually happened.

00:03:40.530 --> 00:03:45.720
There's been some kind of global
catastrophe, a doomsday event.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:48.930
And the vast majority
of humanity has died,

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:52.115
and our civilization
has collapsed.

00:03:52.115 --> 00:03:55.710
But let's say that some
people have survived.

00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:58.850
Let's say that the room
we're in here in Google

00:03:58.850 --> 00:04:01.900
has served as some kind
of hardened bunker,

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:05.740
and we have survived the end
of the world as we know it.

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:09.000
And we stumble outside
in an hour's time

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.180
and find ourselves in the
ruins of the civilization that

00:04:12.180 --> 00:04:14.050
came before us.

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:16.680
Well, what now?

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:20.950
What would you need to
know not just to survive

00:04:20.950 --> 00:04:25.780
in the immediate aftermath,
but to thrive in the long term?

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:28.870
How could you go about
rebuilding a society

00:04:28.870 --> 00:04:31.355
for yourself, a
society from scratch?

00:04:31.355 --> 00:04:32.730
And what could
you do to actually

00:04:32.730 --> 00:04:35.810
accelerate the rebooting
of civilization,

00:04:35.810 --> 00:04:39.090
to recover all of the
science and technology

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:40.690
that we have today?

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:43.000
Could you navigate some
kind of shortcut route

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.120
through that vast
interlinked network

00:04:45.120 --> 00:04:47.950
of scientific discoveries
and new technologies

00:04:47.950 --> 00:04:50.770
that they allow, and their new
scientific discoveries can make

00:04:50.770 --> 00:04:52.929
from applying new technology,
like the telescope

00:04:52.929 --> 00:04:54.720
and the microscope, to
find out new things?

00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:58.000
Could you navigate a shortcut
route through that network

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.650
rather than meandering,
stumbling down blind alleys

00:05:01.650 --> 00:05:04.240
route that we took
the first time around?

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:06.100
So could you
accelerate what took us

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.740
perhaps 10,000
years the first time

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:11.690
and squash that down to
perhaps a few generations

00:05:11.690 --> 00:05:13.240
or a few centuries
if you're trying

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:16.010
to recover from scratch
with hindsight, knowing

00:05:16.010 --> 00:05:17.155
what we know now?

00:05:17.155 --> 00:05:21.900
So in short, if we were to be
a community of survivors, what

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:24.300
would be the one book
that you would want handed

00:05:24.300 --> 00:05:27.610
to you as a manual
for rebuilding

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:30.060
the world from scratch,
to reboot civilization?

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:31.560
And it should come
as no surprise.

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:34.690
And that is the book
that I've tried to write

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:36.080
called, "The Knowledge."

00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:39.000
But I think I should
obviously come clean with you

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.510
right at the beginning.

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:43.849
I do not think the world
is actually about to end.

00:05:43.849 --> 00:05:45.390
I'm not coming from
the point of view

00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:47.160
of a survivalist or a prepper.

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:48.830
I'm not talking
about survival skills

00:05:48.830 --> 00:05:50.790
or how you can skin badgers.

00:05:50.790 --> 00:05:52.550
I've come from the
scientific background.

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:54.510
I'd be very
interested to explore,

00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:59.050
as a thought experiment, all of
the behind the scenes basics.

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:01.842
What are the foundations to
support our modern world?

00:06:01.842 --> 00:06:03.550
What are the things
that we just take for

00:06:03.550 --> 00:06:06.040
granted in our everyday lives?

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:07.670
How does all of that work?

00:06:07.670 --> 00:06:11.300
And importantly, how'd it
develop through history.

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:14.960
What enables civilizations
to progress, and therefore,

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:17.770
how could you try and accelerate
that process the second time

00:06:17.770 --> 00:06:18.866
around?

00:06:18.866 --> 00:06:22.960
And I think a very neat example
of the challenges that we would

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:26.025
face trying to start
everything from scratch

00:06:26.025 --> 00:06:30.380
are presented in an essay
by Leonard Read called,

00:06:30.380 --> 00:06:32.540
"I, Pencil."

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:35.280
Now, the "I, Pencil" isn't some
great new gadget coming out

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:36.874
from Apple.

00:06:36.874 --> 00:06:37.415
It's a story.

00:06:37.415 --> 00:06:41.200
It's a narrative, told from
the point of view of a pencil,

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:44.000
from this simplest
tool or implement

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.600
that we're ever likely
to interact with or use

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:48.760
in our day-to-day lives.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:50.630
It turns out, there's
not a single person

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:54.510
on the planet that knows
how to make a pencil-- no

00:06:54.510 --> 00:06:57.690
one person on the planet,
because of course,

00:06:57.690 --> 00:07:00.980
human knowledge is distributed
across the entire population

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:03.630
from people that know how
to operate a timber mill,

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:06.650
or mining metal ore
out of the ground,

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:10.230
or refining the fuels that
we use to transport and move

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:11.670
everything around.

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:14.240
There's no one person that
knows all the details of all

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:15.050
of those parts.

00:07:15.050 --> 00:07:18.550
And it's just the simplest
part of our everyday lives.

00:07:18.550 --> 00:07:20.970
So imagine multiplying
that amongst all the higher

00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:24.740
technology that we
rely upon today.

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:27.730
And the thought experiment
that I'm talking about here,

00:07:27.730 --> 00:07:29.670
about how to go right
back from scratch

00:07:29.670 --> 00:07:32.270
and preserve the most
valuable knowledge that you

00:07:32.270 --> 00:07:35.820
could has been touched
upon through the years.

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:38.380
There's nothing truly
original or novel about what

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:39.909
I'm talking about here.

00:07:39.909 --> 00:07:42.450
I'm sure many of you would all
know of things like the Global

00:07:42.450 --> 00:07:45.756
Village Construction Set,
or The Toaster Project,

00:07:45.756 --> 00:07:47.630
which is run by a guy
called Thomas Thwaites,

00:07:47.630 --> 00:07:48.799
who also lived in London.

00:07:48.799 --> 00:07:50.590
So I interviewed him
when I was researching

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:51.680
for "The Knowledge."

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:54.260
And he tried to make a
toaster from scratch.

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:57.090
And I don't just mean buying
components and screwdriving

00:07:57.090 --> 00:07:57.990
them together.

00:07:57.990 --> 00:08:00.520
I mean going underground,
there is an iron mine,

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:02.410
and coming out with
some rust colored rocks

00:08:02.410 --> 00:08:06.950
and trying to smelt them in
his back garden and a dustbin.

00:08:06.950 --> 00:08:11.100
And what he produced was this
grotesquely beautiful toaster

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:12.712
at the end, which never worked.

00:08:12.712 --> 00:08:14.420
The first time he
plugged into the mains,

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:15.500
it almost caught fire.

00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:17.870
A great big puff of magic
smoke came out the top.

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:19.310
And it never worked.

00:08:19.310 --> 00:08:21.680
But that's the point
of the project,

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:24.680
to demonstrate just how hard
even the simple things we take

00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:28.150
for granted would be if
you had to make or do them

00:08:28.150 --> 00:08:29.970
yourself from scratch.

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:33.052
And perhaps the earliest
example dates all the way back

00:08:33.052 --> 00:08:36.600
to the 1750s when the
very earliest encyclopedia

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:38.549
writers, people
like Denis Diderot,

00:08:38.549 --> 00:08:42.230
were trying to make a
genuine effort to write down

00:08:42.230 --> 00:08:45.350
the sum total of human knowledge
that was known at that time.

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:47.910
They tried to write the
total book, the book that

00:08:47.910 --> 00:08:49.830
contained everything.

00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:52.820
And Diderot, in fact,
explicitly considered

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:56.270
his duty in compiling and
writing this encyclopedia

00:08:56.270 --> 00:08:59.750
was to serve as a
store of knowledge.

00:08:59.750 --> 00:09:01.520
If civilization
were to collapse,

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:03.520
you would want to store
the most vital knowledge

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:06.190
and protect it as a
seed, as a kernel,

00:09:06.190 --> 00:09:09.190
so you could then
rebuild again afterwards.

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:12.380
Back in the 1750s, people
were much more aware

00:09:12.380 --> 00:09:15.160
of how even great civilizations
can collapse like Rome,

00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:16.412
and Greece, and Egypt.

00:09:16.412 --> 00:09:18.620
And perhaps we're a little
bit more arrogant today at

00:09:18.620 --> 00:09:22.610
how vulnerable
civilizations can be.

00:09:22.610 --> 00:09:26.570
And so the major themes that
I researched and wrote about.

00:09:26.570 --> 00:09:29.380
These are [INAUDIBLE]
the chapters of the book.

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:31.340
Talking about things
from agriculture

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:35.230
and how so few of us today
have any real idea about how

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:38.840
to walk out on muddy field with
a handful of seed and make food

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:41.420
come back out of that field
before the winter draws in

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:43.100
and you starve to
death, or talking

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:45.045
about different
materials and substances.

00:09:45.045 --> 00:09:46.790
If you just reach
into your pocket

00:09:46.790 --> 00:09:48.340
now and pull out
all the things you

00:09:48.340 --> 00:09:50.850
might find in there
from coins, to gadgets,

00:09:50.850 --> 00:09:53.770
or different devices,
even basic stuff,

00:09:53.770 --> 00:09:55.890
like how do you get metal
to come out of rock, out

00:09:55.890 --> 00:09:56.790
of the ore?

00:09:56.790 --> 00:09:58.873
How many people really
know how to do that anymore

00:09:58.873 --> 00:10:01.710
and yet, think how vital
materials like metals

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:03.201
really are?

00:10:03.201 --> 00:10:04.950
And doing the talk,
I'll skip through some

00:10:04.950 --> 00:10:06.325
of these other
areas of medicine,

00:10:06.325 --> 00:10:08.670
and power, and communication.

00:10:08.670 --> 00:10:11.800
But actually, the chapter that
I found most satisfying, again,

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:15.425
as a mini thought experiment
to research and write about

00:10:15.425 --> 00:10:17.700
was this penultimate
chapter, time and place.

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:19.450
And again, the thought
experiment for this

00:10:19.450 --> 00:10:22.250
might be imagine you
wake up from a coma,

00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:24.690
or you stumble out
of a cryogenic pod,

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:26.440
or you've fallen
through a time warp,

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:29.120
and you find yourself
somewhere on the earth

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:31.000
at some point in the future.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.970
But you have no idea where
you are or when you are.

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:38.130
So what simple
observations can you make?

00:10:38.130 --> 00:10:40.600
How can you work
from first principles

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:44.950
to calculate where on the planet
you are, what address you are,

00:10:44.950 --> 00:10:46.534
what latitude and
longitude you're at.

00:10:46.534 --> 00:10:48.574
But also, when you are,
not just the time of day,

00:10:48.574 --> 00:10:49.710
not if it's at lunch time.

00:10:49.710 --> 00:10:52.040
You can build a sundial
relatively easily.

00:10:52.040 --> 00:10:53.465
But what is the date?

00:10:53.465 --> 00:10:54.590
What day of the year is it?

00:10:54.590 --> 00:10:57.262
How could you reconstruct
the calendar from scratch

00:10:57.262 --> 00:10:58.720
or even work out
what year it might

00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:02.000
be 10,000 years in the
future from observing things

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:02.940
around you?

00:11:02.940 --> 00:11:05.530
And again, these aren't
frivolous exercises.

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:07.880
Being able to work out
where you on the planet

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:11.225
is the absolute essence, is the
prerequisite for navigation,

00:11:11.225 --> 00:11:13.835
and exploring the
oceans, and trading.

00:11:13.835 --> 00:11:16.210
And being able to track your
progress through the seasons

00:11:16.210 --> 00:11:18.830
and using the calendar is
an absolute prerequisite

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:20.500
for agriculture,
and making sure you

00:11:20.500 --> 00:11:22.140
put your seeds in the
ground at the right time,

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:24.220
and take them out at the
right time for harvest

00:11:24.220 --> 00:11:26.790
so you don't starve to death.

