00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:55.590
you'd be afforded
a grace period.

00:11:55.590 --> 00:11:58.020
You wouldn't have to work out
the very first morning when

00:11:58.020 --> 00:11:59.770
you wake up with a
hangover from the night

00:11:59.770 --> 00:12:01.360
before when the world,
as we know, has ended.

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:03.609
You wouldn't have to work
out agriculture for yourself

00:12:03.609 --> 00:12:05.295
immediately, because
you could scavenge

00:12:05.295 --> 00:12:08.080
and forage for what you need.

00:12:08.080 --> 00:12:11.070
And particularly
within food, today, we

00:12:11.070 --> 00:12:14.630
are exceedingly good at
preserving and stockpiling

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:15.130
food.

00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:16.860
We create artificial winter.

00:12:16.860 --> 00:12:20.180
We exploit the gas laws to
make refrigerators and freezers

00:12:20.180 --> 00:12:22.540
to preserve food, and
particularly, the canning

00:12:22.540 --> 00:12:23.660
process.

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:26.620
This food will remain
good for decades.

00:12:26.620 --> 00:12:28.750
So again, as a
thought experiment,

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:30.790
I wanted to know,
if I was locked

00:12:30.790 --> 00:12:33.200
in an average supermarket,
how long could I

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:36.810
survive for before I'd
either eaten all of the food

00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:40.072
or I'd gone off before I
could get around to eating it?

00:12:40.072 --> 00:12:41.780
And conveniently, the
average supermarket

00:12:41.780 --> 00:12:43.488
was the one just down
the road from where

00:12:43.488 --> 00:12:45.060
I live in North London.

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:46.800
And I walked up and
down all the aisles,

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:48.980
multiplying up all of
the food that was there,

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:50.438
dividing it by the
amount you would

00:12:50.438 --> 00:12:52.260
need to eat per day to survive.

00:12:52.260 --> 00:12:54.440
And it turns out that
a single supermarket

00:12:54.440 --> 00:13:00.380
could keep you alive for
55 years, or 63 years,

00:13:00.380 --> 00:13:03.940
if you're happy to eat all the
canned dog food and cat food,

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:04.440
as well.

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:06.452
There's a vast reserve
of food lying around

00:13:06.452 --> 00:13:07.910
that you could keep
yourself going,

00:13:07.910 --> 00:13:10.630
you could coast upon,
dine out on the leftovers,

00:13:10.630 --> 00:13:12.750
whilst you work out
through trial and error

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:16.140
how to do farming for yourself,
before that food runs out

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:19.260
and it becomes a matter
of life and death.

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:21.290
And obviously, beyond
food, drinking water

00:13:21.290 --> 00:13:26.720
is another absolute
requirement for a healthy life.

00:13:26.720 --> 00:13:28.840
So how can you apply
modern knowledge,

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:31.580
modern understanding,
to know for a fact

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:33.290
the water you're
about to put your lips

00:13:33.290 --> 00:13:35.550
and drink is not
going to kill you?

00:13:35.550 --> 00:13:38.976
That doesn't contain cholera,
or typhoid, or any other number

00:13:38.976 --> 00:13:40.350
of waterborne
diseases which have

00:13:40.350 --> 00:13:43.642
been the scourge of
humanity throughout history?

00:13:43.642 --> 00:13:45.850
And again, if you're scavenging
through the abandoned

00:13:45.850 --> 00:13:47.910
supermarkets and
dead cities, you

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:49.690
could get things
like kitchen bleach.

00:13:49.690 --> 00:13:53.465
And if you dilute kitchen bleach
enough-- do not drink it neat.

00:13:53.465 --> 00:13:55.800
If you dilute kitchen
bleach enough,

00:13:55.800 --> 00:13:57.630
you can chemically
disinfect the water,

00:13:57.630 --> 00:13:58.870
and it'll be safe to drink.

00:13:58.870 --> 00:14:01.172
You're exploiting the
chemistry of chlorine

00:14:01.172 --> 00:14:03.630
in exactly the same way the
water coming out of the faucets

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.590
is treated with
chlorine to disinfect

00:14:05.590 --> 00:14:06.710
and make it safe to drink.

00:14:06.710 --> 00:14:08.770
If you can't find
any kitchen bleach,

00:14:08.770 --> 00:14:11.030
you can use swimming
pool chlorine.

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:14.260
So sodium hypochlorite
or calcium hypochlorite

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:16.520
will disinfect water for you.

00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:18.580
But actually, there's
an even simpler way,

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:22.600
a process called SODIS,
or solar disinfection,

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:25.500
which has been touted by the
World Health Organization

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:28.105
around the developing world
to break the disease cycle

00:14:28.105 --> 00:14:31.540
and stop hundreds of thousands
of people dying of diarrhea.

00:14:31.540 --> 00:14:34.790
And all you need to do is
fill an empty plastic bottle

00:14:34.790 --> 00:14:37.770
with water and
leave it in the sun.

00:14:37.770 --> 00:14:39.530
And because that
bottle is essentially

00:14:39.530 --> 00:14:41.665
constraining the water
to be very shallow,

00:14:41.665 --> 00:14:43.320
the ultraviolet rays
and the sunlight

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:46.390
can shine straight through
and kill any pathogens

00:14:46.390 --> 00:14:47.140
that are in there.

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:50.150
You can come back a day or
two later, drink that water,

00:14:50.150 --> 00:14:54.010
and know for a fact
that it's safe to drink.

00:14:54.010 --> 00:14:57.720
Now, fire, as well, has
been an absolute foundation

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:00.350
of society for millennia,
for thousands and thousands

00:15:00.350 --> 00:15:01.477
of years.

00:15:01.477 --> 00:15:03.810
But again, I suspect there's
not many people in the room

00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:06.130
here, if you couldn't
reach for a box of matches

00:15:06.130 --> 00:15:08.836
or for a lighter, could
you actually get a fire

00:15:08.836 --> 00:15:09.710
started for yourself?

00:15:09.710 --> 00:15:12.080
How many people know how
to rub sticks together

00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:14.667
to ignite a fire successfully?

00:15:14.667 --> 00:15:17.000
And we don't just use fire
for cooking food, and killing

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.230
germs, and keeping us warm.

00:15:19.230 --> 00:15:23.310
Civilization uses fire to take
the base stuff that we dig out

00:15:23.310 --> 00:15:26.830
of the ground and transform it
into the most useful substances

00:15:26.830 --> 00:15:28.635
and materials of history.

00:15:28.635 --> 00:15:32.460
We use fire to take
river mud, clay,

00:15:32.460 --> 00:15:34.500
and turn it into bricks
we use for building.

00:15:34.500 --> 00:15:37.787
We use fire to get metal
out of rock, out of the ore.

00:15:37.787 --> 00:15:39.995
And we use fire to drive
all of the crucial chemistry

00:15:39.995 --> 00:15:42.330
that our society depends
upon, like making

00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:45.790
artificial fertilizers that
feed over 2 billion people

00:15:45.790 --> 00:15:47.040
on the planet today.

00:15:47.040 --> 00:15:50.220
Our modern world is
as reliant on fire

00:15:50.220 --> 00:15:53.670
as a Stone Age family
huddled around the campfire.

00:15:53.670 --> 00:15:57.240
We've just hidden it behind
the scenes in our factories

00:15:57.240 --> 00:15:58.340
and power stations.

00:15:58.340 --> 00:16:01.409
But it's still as critical.

00:16:01.409 --> 00:16:02.700
So how do you get a fire going?

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:05.880
I've got a quick
video to show you,

00:16:05.880 --> 00:16:08.465
which we filmed for
the book coming out

00:16:08.465 --> 00:16:10.990
in hardback last year.

00:16:10.990 --> 00:16:14.690
And this is about how you
can use unusual combinations

00:16:14.690 --> 00:16:17.190
of everyday items to
start a fire if you

00:16:17.190 --> 00:16:19.990
can't find matches or lighters.

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:23.240
And this one is how we can use
a smoke detector or a fire alarm

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:25.240
to start a fire, paradoxically.

00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:31.430
So the way that you start
a fire with a fire alarm,

00:16:31.430 --> 00:16:35.200
with a smoke detector,
is to pop off the back

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:38.150
and take out the batteries
that you find inside.

00:16:38.150 --> 00:16:41.495
And specifically, the nine volt
batteries, which are special,

00:16:41.495 --> 00:16:42.870
because out of
the two terminals,

00:16:42.870 --> 00:16:46.780
the positive and next terminal,
both are at the same end.

00:16:46.780 --> 00:16:50.450
And if you also scavenge
from an abandoned supermarket

00:16:50.450 --> 00:16:55.330
or house some steel wool, you
can short circuit the battery

00:16:55.330 --> 00:16:56.520
through steel wool.

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:58.570
Do not do this at home.

00:16:58.570 --> 00:17:00.840
But totally have a
go at this at home.

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:03.280
And if you brush ever so
gently and then blow on it

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:08.470
with any kindling, you can get
that metal to absolutely burst

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:09.180
into flames.

00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:12.130
This isn't trying newspaper
or kindling burning.

00:17:12.130 --> 00:17:15.329
That's the metal itself
bursting into flames.

00:17:15.329 --> 00:17:18.676
And if you can crack the
trick-- so obviously, what

00:17:18.676 --> 00:17:20.259
we're exploiting
here is the principle

00:17:20.259 --> 00:17:21.190
of electrical resistance.

00:17:21.190 --> 00:17:22.599
You're passing a current
through a very thin wire

00:17:22.599 --> 00:17:25.800
with very high resistance, so it
gets hot and burst into flames.

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:28.910
If you can crack the trick of
getting a thin wire very hot

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:30.820
and not burst into
flames, you've

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:32.060
just invented the light bulb.

00:17:32.060 --> 00:17:34.210
It's exactly what
Edison solved to exploit

00:17:34.210 --> 00:17:36.720
exactly the same principle.

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:38.610
And so electricity,
as well, as it's

00:17:38.610 --> 00:17:41.845
been a foundation of
our modern society.

00:17:41.845 --> 00:17:43.580
And what I try to do
throughout the book,

00:17:43.580 --> 00:17:45.480
throughout "The
Knowledge," was to keep

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:48.150
basing the things I'm
talking about on real world

00:17:48.150 --> 00:17:50.570
examples, not
arm-waving speculation,

00:17:50.570 --> 00:17:53.700
but occasions in history
where people have solved

00:17:53.700 --> 00:17:57.080
challenges and problems
in particular ways.

00:17:57.080 --> 00:17:59.140
And what we're looking
at here is a city

00:17:59.140 --> 00:18:02.470
called Gorazde, which during
the mid-1990s in the Bosnian

00:18:02.470 --> 00:18:06.270
Serbian War, this city was
surrounded by the Army,

00:18:06.270 --> 00:18:09.480
and isolated, cut off
from rest of the world.

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:13.540
And although NATO was able to
get food and medication dropped

00:18:13.540 --> 00:18:15.700
to them, they were cut off
of the electrical grid.

00:18:15.700 --> 00:18:17.520
They were thrown back
into the Middle Ages

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:20.720
in the sense of this
component to our modern world.

00:18:20.720 --> 00:18:23.440
And so what the inhabitants
of Gorazde were able to do

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:26.180
was scavenge and forage from
rubbish, junk just lying

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:27.310
around their city.

00:18:27.310 --> 00:18:30.100
And doing junkyard
wars, but for real, they

00:18:30.100 --> 00:18:32.460
made these water
wheels, which they

00:18:32.460 --> 00:18:34.840
dunked into the river in
the fast-flowing stream

00:18:34.840 --> 00:18:37.260
tethered to the bridge here.

00:18:37.260 --> 00:18:39.930
And the crucial component
right in the middle of each

00:18:39.930 --> 00:18:42.510
of these water wheels, the thing
that converts that rotation

00:18:42.510 --> 00:18:45.994
into electricity, is an
alternator, a component

00:18:45.994 --> 00:18:47.410
you can scavenge
under the bonnet,

00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:49.610
under the hood of any
car or abandoned truck

00:18:49.610 --> 00:18:51.710
you find lying around,
and just jury rig

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:55.520
stuff together to keep your
civilized lifestyle going.

00:18:55.520 --> 00:18:58.095
I think it's an incredible
example of the ingenuity

00:18:58.095 --> 00:19:00.960
and resourcefulness of
just everyday people

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:02.640
under challenging circumstances.

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:04.181
This is the kind of
skills you'd want

00:19:04.181 --> 00:19:07.110
to try and apply to rebuilding
society again from scratch

00:19:07.110 --> 00:19:09.580
yourself after an apocalypse.

00:19:09.580 --> 00:19:13.204
But sooner or later, this grace
period will draw to an end.

00:19:13.204 --> 00:19:15.120
Things will run out, or
decay, or deteriorate,

00:19:15.120 --> 00:19:19.250
or you'll just have used them
up without making them yourself.

00:19:19.250 --> 00:19:21.420
And particularly
with agriculture,

00:19:21.420 --> 00:19:24.035
the most important
plant in history

00:19:24.035 --> 00:19:26.520
have been these,
the cereal crops,

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:30.790
and in particular, the first
three-- wheat, rice, and maize,

00:19:30.790 --> 00:19:35.070
which have supported all of the
civilizations of Europe, Asia,

00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:37.790
and the Americas.

00:19:37.790 --> 00:19:41.385
And the dependence of humanity
throughout civilization,

00:19:41.385 --> 00:19:43.940
our dependence on
these cereal crops,

00:19:43.940 --> 00:19:46.270
it means that throughout
history, humanity

00:19:46.270 --> 00:19:49.210
has survived by
eating grass, just

00:19:49.210 --> 00:19:51.290
like our cows and our sheep.

00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:55.330
The cereal crops evolved as
fast-growing species of grass.

00:19:55.330 --> 00:19:58.335
They make an ideal plant
to eat in that sense.

00:19:58.335 --> 00:20:00.450
But we had a problem.

00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:05.760
The kernel of wheat is a
fabulous nugget of nutrition.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:08.320
But it's hard and indigestible.

00:20:08.320 --> 00:20:09.930
So we need to break
down that grain

00:20:09.930 --> 00:20:13.530
to release nutrients to
be absorbed by our bodies.

00:20:13.530 --> 00:20:15.390
And the main inventions
through history

00:20:15.390 --> 00:20:19.020
that have helped with this
have been the Roman water wheel

00:20:19.020 --> 00:20:20.990
and the medieval windmill.

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:22.780
These are obviously
ways of harnessing

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:26.600
natural power sources,
hydropower and wind power.

00:20:26.600 --> 00:20:29.040
But the crucial components
of both of these

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:32.920
is this pair of cylindrical
slabs, the millstones which

00:20:32.920 --> 00:20:36.530
turn over each other and
grind that grain into flour.

00:20:36.530 --> 00:20:39.305
This is a relic of Stone
Age technology right

00:20:39.305 --> 00:20:42.130
in the heart of the complex
mechanisms of the windmill

00:20:42.130 --> 00:20:43.320
here.

00:20:43.320 --> 00:20:45.770
And we take that
flour, and we cook it.

00:20:45.770 --> 00:20:47.636
We bake bread.

00:20:47.636 --> 00:20:49.760
And the heat of the fire
that we use for cooking

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:52.820
makes the food tastes
nice, but more importantly,

00:20:52.820 --> 00:20:55.270
helps to break down that
nutrition so that we

00:20:55.270 --> 00:20:57.510
can absorb it into our bodies.

00:20:57.510 --> 00:21:00.770
So in a very real
sense, the millstone

00:21:00.770 --> 00:21:03.965
is like a technological
extension of our own molar

00:21:03.965 --> 00:21:05.040
teeth.

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:07.043
And the oven we use for
baking bread, or the pot

00:21:07.043 --> 00:21:11.080
we use for boiling rice is
like an external predigestive

00:21:11.080 --> 00:21:12.070
system.

00:21:12.070 --> 00:21:13.780
Humanity doesn't
have the benefit

00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:15.410
of four stomachs like a cow.

00:21:15.410 --> 00:21:17.990
We're biologically
disadvantaged in that sense.

00:21:17.990 --> 00:21:21.320
So we've had to adopt technology
to enable us to live off

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:24.890
fast-growing species of grass.

00:21:24.890 --> 00:21:26.710
Now again, I suspect
not many people

00:21:26.710 --> 00:21:30.200
would know where to go to pick
up some seed corn or some wheat

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:33.450
that you can put in the
ground and grow and harvest.

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:35.470
And so this is
where you would go.

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:38.880
This is the Svalbard
Global Seed Vault.

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:40.050
This is the front door.

00:21:40.050 --> 00:21:41.430
These are blast proof doors.

00:21:41.430 --> 00:21:44.865
This place could genuinely
survive a nuclear exchange.

00:21:44.865 --> 00:21:47.240
And the fact that it's built
into the side of a mountain,

00:21:47.240 --> 00:21:49.281
away from the Arctic
Circle, means the permafrost

00:21:49.281 --> 00:21:52.830
of the mountain around it, that
even if the grid goes down,

00:21:52.830 --> 00:21:54.900
this thing would remain
naturally refrigerated

00:21:54.900 --> 00:21:57.410
for hundreds, if not
thousands of years.

00:21:57.410 --> 00:21:59.520
You would hope that
when you got here,

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:03.040
someone had left the door key
under the mat at the front

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:04.990
so you could open those doors.

00:22:04.990 --> 00:22:08.446
But this is designed to be
like a biological safe file,

00:22:08.446 --> 00:22:11.774
a genetic library of all of
the major crops we grow today.

00:22:11.774 --> 00:22:13.190
And this is exactly
where you want

00:22:13.190 --> 00:22:16.620
to go to get wheat, or
rice, or any other cereal

00:22:16.620 --> 00:22:19.050
crops or other crops that
you would need to reboot

00:22:19.050 --> 00:22:20.670
agriculture for yourself.

00:22:20.670 --> 00:22:23.100
If you don't know
where Svalbard is,

00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:25.240
I've very helpfully
for you, provided

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:27.820
the latitude and longitude
coordinates that you'd go to.

00:22:27.820 --> 00:22:29.862
And if you don't know your
latitude and longitude

00:22:29.862 --> 00:22:32.236
coordinates, if you don't know
what your address is right

00:22:32.236 --> 00:22:34.680
here, and therefore, what
direction to start heading in,

00:22:34.680 --> 00:22:36.740
turn to that time and
place chapter in the book.

00:22:36.740 --> 00:22:39.460
And I explain to you
from first principles,

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:41.790
using stuff around you,
how you can determine

00:22:41.790 --> 00:22:43.470
exactly where you
are, and therefore,

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:45.060
how to navigate to there.

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:46.795
So as far as
possible, everything

00:22:46.795 --> 00:22:48.920
within "The Knowledge,"
everything within the book,

00:22:48.920 --> 00:22:50.620
interlinks to everything else.

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:53.260
I don't assume any prior
or external knowledge.

00:22:53.260 --> 00:22:55.089
I contain as far
as I can everything

00:22:55.089 --> 00:22:56.380
you'll need in this one manual.

