of the substances
tree are things

00:23:30.830 --> 00:23:34.070
like lime and soda, which you
may not have even ever heard

00:23:34.070 --> 00:23:36.600
of, but they are the most
fundamentally important things

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:39.800
that you rely upon day upon
day in our everyday lives

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:40.610
without realizing.

00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:43.212
And I explain how to
make lime for yourself

00:23:43.212 --> 00:23:45.670
or soda for yourself and how
to use soda to make everything

00:23:45.670 --> 00:23:48.870
from paper, to soap, to glass,
how you start with glass,

00:23:48.870 --> 00:23:51.642
and then you can now grind
lenses to make lenses,

00:23:51.642 --> 00:23:53.100
to make telescopes
and microscopes,

00:23:53.100 --> 00:23:56.350
and use microscopes to discover
germs to stop you getting sick.

00:23:56.350 --> 00:23:57.767
So all of this,
links in together.

00:23:57.767 --> 00:23:59.808
There are ingredients and
ingredients and recipes

00:23:59.808 --> 00:24:02.380
in the book as to how to
do all that basic chemistry

00:24:02.380 --> 00:24:04.390
for yourself.

00:24:04.390 --> 00:24:07.060
And within transport,
what you would really

00:24:07.060 --> 00:24:10.640
hope that your post-apocalyptic
society, that you could stop

00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:15.460
the regression before you reach
a state like this where you can

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:17.450
no longer run mechanization.

00:24:17.450 --> 00:24:19.990
You've lost engines
and machinery.

00:24:19.990 --> 00:24:22.780
And this is more important
than just jumping in your car

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:24.240
and nipping down the road.

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:26.760
We use machinery and
internal combustion engine

00:24:26.760 --> 00:24:28.680
for doing everything
in the world around us,

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:31.415
and releasing the effort
of our own muscles.

00:24:31.415 --> 00:24:35.460
So the question is, how can you
run machinery without access

00:24:35.460 --> 00:24:37.260
to crude oil, and the
diesel, and gasoline

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:40.100
that are refined from it?

00:24:40.100 --> 00:24:43.270
I've got another video that
I'm going to load up briefly.

00:24:43.270 --> 00:24:46.500
So this is the point on the TED
stage last week where I almost

00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:48.720
set fire to my own head.

00:24:48.720 --> 00:24:50.470
So I'm not going to
do that indoors again.

00:24:50.470 --> 00:24:53.580
I'm going to show you the video.

00:24:53.580 --> 00:24:57.320
So what we've got is a
gasifier stove, it's called.

00:24:57.320 --> 00:25:00.980
And I made this one myself
out of some old junk tin cans.

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:04.610
And there's a big outer can,
and a smaller can inside it,

00:25:04.610 --> 00:25:06.555
and holes at the bottom of both.

00:25:06.555 --> 00:25:08.180
So when you put some
newspaper and just

00:25:08.180 --> 00:25:11.690
a small handful of twigs in
the inner can and light it,

00:25:11.690 --> 00:25:14.540
it draws air up through
the bottom of that fire

00:25:14.540 --> 00:25:18.620
to keep it nice and intense,
just like any barbecue.

00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:21.240
But what is unique about
this gasifier stove

00:25:21.240 --> 00:25:24.535
is that there is a second row
of holes right at the top.

00:25:24.535 --> 00:25:27.710
So as the wood breaks down
and the heat of that fire

00:25:27.710 --> 00:25:32.480
undergoes pyrolysis, it releases
lots of gases, and vapors,

00:25:32.480 --> 00:25:35.420
and smoke, which is
itself combustible.

00:25:35.420 --> 00:25:38.300
And you then reintroduce
oxygen into that hot gas mix,

00:25:38.300 --> 00:25:40.814
and combust everything
at that point.

00:25:40.814 --> 00:25:42.230
So when this is
up and running, it

00:25:42.230 --> 00:25:45.510
is smokeless, and
exceedingly efficient.

00:25:45.510 --> 00:25:49.390
And just to show you how
effective one of these really

00:25:49.390 --> 00:25:52.830
primitive, simple
gasifier stoves can be,

00:25:52.830 --> 00:25:55.610
this is me in a garage
in London demonstrating.

00:25:55.610 --> 00:25:58.140
And if you just
watch, I've genuinely

00:25:58.140 --> 00:26:01.290
put only a tiny handful of
little bits of twig in there.

00:26:01.290 --> 00:26:04.040
There's very little fuel that
I'm loading this up with.

00:26:06.680 --> 00:26:09.240
And in seconds, I'm going
to light this gas fire

00:26:09.240 --> 00:26:11.060
stove using a lighter.

00:26:11.060 --> 00:26:13.240
But I hope that I've
convinced you at this point

00:26:13.240 --> 00:26:15.365
that I could've used a
smoke detector if I'd really

00:26:15.365 --> 00:26:18.720
wanted to to get the gasifier
stove up and running.

00:26:21.919 --> 00:26:25.390
And it smokes a little bit
as it first gets going.

00:26:25.390 --> 00:26:28.400
But if you watch,
as I put the flue

00:26:28.400 --> 00:26:30.860
on top, which again, is just
made from small tin cans,

00:26:30.860 --> 00:26:33.150
within about four
seconds, the smoke

00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:37.620
disappears and is replaced
by this 4 foot jet of flame

00:26:37.620 --> 00:26:39.905
coming out at the top.

00:26:39.905 --> 00:26:44.260
So this is the airflow
coming up through that fire,

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:46.645
and the second row of
air holes combusting

00:26:46.645 --> 00:26:49.020
all of those producer gases,
the gases that are given off

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:50.436
by the wood as it
breaks down the,

00:26:50.436 --> 00:26:52.197
that would otherwise
have just flown away

00:26:52.197 --> 00:26:53.280
and then blow in the wind.

00:26:53.280 --> 00:26:56.065
These kind of things are
also called rocket stoves

00:26:56.065 --> 00:26:59.720
for perhaps obvious reasons.

00:26:59.720 --> 00:27:01.800
If I take off the flue,
you can see how effective

00:27:01.800 --> 00:27:04.930
this is at releasing
all of the energy that's

00:27:04.930 --> 00:27:06.660
been locked up in the wood.

00:27:06.660 --> 00:27:08.340
And we've zoomed
in now to the top.

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:11.070
You can see these jets
of flame coming in

00:27:11.070 --> 00:27:12.510
from that upper
row of air holes,

00:27:12.510 --> 00:27:16.050
where those producer gases are
combusted when you mix oxygen

00:27:16.050 --> 00:27:18.410
with them again.

00:27:18.410 --> 00:27:20.670
And this is exactly
the kind of technology,

00:27:20.670 --> 00:27:23.190
the appropriate technology,
or intermediate technology

00:27:23.190 --> 00:27:26.870
that has been touted around the
developing world by development

00:27:26.870 --> 00:27:29.730
agencies, because you can make
this kind of stuff yourself.

00:27:29.730 --> 00:27:31.620
It doesn't require
any high tech.

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:33.459
The fact that it's
smokeless means

00:27:33.459 --> 00:27:35.000
it's much, much
healthier for cooking

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.489
with in closed,
cramped conditions.

00:27:37.489 --> 00:27:39.030
And the fact that
it's very efficient

00:27:39.030 --> 00:27:41.238
means it makes the most
effective use of the firewood

00:27:41.238 --> 00:27:43.080
the family can collect.

00:27:43.080 --> 00:27:46.920
But what you can do is scale up
a gasifier stove from something

00:27:46.920 --> 00:27:49.860
the size of a soup can,
like this, to something

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:55.250
the size of a trash can,
strap it to the back of a car.

00:27:55.250 --> 00:27:58.590
And you can run a car
using wood as fuel

00:27:58.590 --> 00:28:00.950
rather than oil, or
gasoline, or diesel.

00:28:00.950 --> 00:28:03.300
This is the gasifier
on the back.

00:28:03.300 --> 00:28:05.290
And so the wood is
breaking down on the heat,

00:28:05.290 --> 00:28:06.831
releasing those
producer gases, which

00:28:06.831 --> 00:28:09.740
are piped over the roof of
the car, down into the engine,

00:28:09.740 --> 00:28:11.580
with a final ultimate
mix with oxygen

00:28:11.580 --> 00:28:15.180
and explode usefully
to drive this car.

00:28:15.180 --> 00:28:17.050
Now, I'll admit
to you, this does

00:28:17.050 --> 00:28:20.050
look like some kind of crazy
steampunk post-apocalyptic Mad

00:28:20.050 --> 00:28:21.750
Max contraption.

00:28:21.750 --> 00:28:23.490
But it works.

00:28:23.490 --> 00:28:27.950
And this isn't just some
kind of fringe hobby.

00:28:27.950 --> 00:28:32.890
During the Second World War and
all of the oil shortages back

00:28:32.890 --> 00:28:35.740
then, there were over
a million gasifier

00:28:35.740 --> 00:28:39.430
powered cars, wood powered
cars across Europe.

00:28:39.430 --> 00:28:42.580
This is exactly the kind
of intermediate technology

00:28:42.580 --> 00:28:45.750
you could stop the further
regression of your society

00:28:45.750 --> 00:28:50.990
and start pulling yourself
back up by your own bootstraps.

00:28:50.990 --> 00:28:53.090
If we turn to materials,
I've already shown

00:28:53.090 --> 00:28:56.610
you the substances tree and how
you extract things like metal

00:28:56.610 --> 00:28:58.450
from the rock, from
ore, and how we've

00:28:58.450 --> 00:29:00.020
done that through history.

00:29:00.020 --> 00:29:02.020
But that's only going to
be half of the problem.

00:29:02.020 --> 00:29:04.060
You've also got
to make something

00:29:04.060 --> 00:29:05.730
useful out of that metal.

00:29:05.730 --> 00:29:09.642
You've got to transform a
lump of metal into a tool.

00:29:09.642 --> 00:29:11.100
And what I was also
very, very keen

00:29:11.100 --> 00:29:13.990
to do when I was researching
for the two or three

00:29:13.990 --> 00:29:16.369
years of "The
Knowledge" project,

00:29:16.369 --> 00:29:18.160
I didn't want to just
sit down in libraries

00:29:18.160 --> 00:29:20.118
and learn from books or
by interviewing people.

00:29:20.118 --> 00:29:23.199
I wanted to get some firsthand,
hands-on experience doing

00:29:23.199 --> 00:29:25.865
stuff for myself so I could then
write about it with experience.

00:29:25.865 --> 00:29:29.620
So I spent a day in a
traditional 16th century

00:29:29.620 --> 00:29:31.690
blacksmith, an iron forge.

00:29:31.690 --> 00:29:34.980
And when you think about it, the
kind of craft of the blacksmith

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:36.420
is really simple.

00:29:36.420 --> 00:29:39.830
You take a big pile of fuel,
either charcoal or coke,

00:29:39.830 --> 00:29:41.980
set fire to it, and
force air through it

00:29:41.980 --> 00:29:44.720
with a set of bellows so
it gets really, really hot.

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:47.130
You take your lump of metal
you want to start working on,

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:50.900
shove it on a hot place until
it gets very hot and then soft,

00:29:50.900 --> 00:29:52.900
and then hit it with
another lump of metal which

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:55.160
is still cold, and
therefore, still very hard.

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:58.190
You use iron to work on iron.

00:29:58.190 --> 00:30:01.170
So I felt very smug with
myself after spending a day

00:30:01.170 --> 00:30:04.490
bashing the hell out of this
bit of metal, this lump of iron

00:30:04.490 --> 00:30:07.935
on a hammer and anvil
and made for myself

00:30:07.935 --> 00:30:11.020
a tool, made a knife, which
you can come up and have a look

00:30:11.020 --> 00:30:14.160
at afterwards if you'd like.

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:17.300
And the very first thing
I did when I got back home

00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:19.580
was march straight
into the kitchen

00:30:19.580 --> 00:30:21.950
and use the knife that
I'd made with my own hands

00:30:21.950 --> 00:30:25.290
to cut a loaf, cut some
cheese, and make myself

00:30:25.290 --> 00:30:28.145
a post-apocalyptic grilled
cheese from scratch.

00:30:28.145 --> 00:30:30.740
I was absurdly smug with myself.

00:30:30.740 --> 00:30:33.230
But if you look more closely,
either on the picture here

00:30:33.230 --> 00:30:36.360
or by coming up and having a
look at the actual artifact,

00:30:36.360 --> 00:30:38.790
I notice that there's
a ruinous crack where

00:30:38.790 --> 00:30:41.210
the handle meets the blade.

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:44.814
I'd never had the guts to go
back and try my knife again.

00:30:44.814 --> 00:30:47.230
So I've actually done quite a
bad job of making this tool,

00:30:47.230 --> 00:30:49.830
making this knife from scratch.

00:30:49.830 --> 00:30:52.490
But the important thing
is I know what went wrong.

00:30:52.490 --> 00:30:55.640
I know how to go back and
have another try, another go,

00:30:55.640 --> 00:30:56.530
and improve.

00:30:56.530 --> 00:30:59.180
And so as a
microcosm, this knife

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:02.555
represents how we have advanced
and progressed through history,

00:31:02.555 --> 00:31:05.320
through this reiterative
cycle of trial and error,

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:09.490
and applying your rationality
and critical thinking

00:31:09.490 --> 00:31:11.530
to work out why
something has failed,

00:31:11.530 --> 00:31:14.920
and therefore, improve upon
it next time to bug hunt

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:17.210
and fix those issues.

00:31:17.210 --> 00:31:22.440
Within communication, the
kind of gateway technology,

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:25.646
the thing you'd want to
leapfrog immediately back to

00:31:25.646 --> 00:31:28.380
would be something like
the printing press,

00:31:28.380 --> 00:31:30.000
because before the
printing press,

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:31.380
if you wanted to
copy a document,

00:31:31.380 --> 00:31:33.500
if you wanted to
share your ideas,

00:31:33.500 --> 00:31:36.430
the only way of doing that would
be having a room full of people

00:31:36.430 --> 00:31:38.250
copying things out by hand.

00:31:38.250 --> 00:31:40.530
This is enormously
time consuming,

00:31:40.530 --> 00:31:43.290
and laborious, and expensive.

00:31:43.290 --> 00:31:45.230
And that means that
only rich people

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:48.635
get to choose what ideas
are allowed to spread.

00:31:48.635 --> 00:31:51.010
But with the invention
of the printing press,

00:31:51.010 --> 00:31:53.420
knowledge itself,
human understanding

00:31:53.420 --> 00:31:54.490
becomes democratized.

00:31:54.490 --> 00:31:58.100
Anyone can share any ideas
they want with everyone else.

00:31:58.100 --> 00:32:00.670
And that accelerates
not just technology

00:32:00.670 --> 00:32:03.570
and scientific discussion,
but political ideologies

00:32:03.570 --> 00:32:05.120
and philosophies.

00:32:05.120 --> 00:32:09.040
It accelerates many areas of
your society at the same time.

00:32:09.040 --> 00:32:11.530
And this is exactly, again,
the kind of technology

00:32:11.530 --> 00:32:14.320
you want to leapfrog
as quickly as possible

00:32:14.320 --> 00:32:17.147
to help rebooting
your civilization.

00:32:17.147 --> 00:32:19.730
Now, another thing I was very,
very smug about when I realized

00:32:19.730 --> 00:32:22.510
I could pull this off
was that within the pages

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:24.350
of "The Knowledge,"
I explain how

00:32:24.350 --> 00:32:26.760
to make your own
paper from scratch.

00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:28.940
I explain how to
make your own ink.

00:32:28.940 --> 00:32:32.360
And I explain how to construct
a rudimentary printing press.

00:32:32.360 --> 00:32:34.920
So it's almost as if, within
the pages of "The Knowledge,"

00:32:34.920 --> 00:32:37.150
it contains the
genetic instructions

00:32:37.150 --> 00:32:38.800
for its own reproduction.

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:42.780
Tongue in cheek, of course,
only one copy of this manual

00:32:42.780 --> 00:32:44.590
would need to survive
the apocalypse.

00:32:44.590 --> 00:32:46.880
And it tells people how
to reproduce it and then

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:49.090
hand out copies to
everyone that survived

00:32:49.090 --> 00:32:50.220
and might need to know.

00:32:50.220 --> 00:32:52.520
And just as a proof
of principle, here's

00:32:52.520 --> 00:32:54.480
a few pages of the
book-- the page

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:57.060
about how to build a
printing press printed

00:32:57.060 --> 00:32:59.950
on a rudimentary printing
press, on handmade paper.

00:32:59.950 --> 00:33:03.210
This is the proof of
the concept there.

00:33:03.210 --> 00:33:06.740
That's going to fall over.

00:33:06.740 --> 00:33:11.520
The very final thing that
I was going to mention

00:33:11.520 --> 00:33:12.670
was in advanced chemistry.

00:33:12.670 --> 00:33:15.130
And I've shown to you
the capabilities tree

00:33:15.130 --> 00:33:18.030
of simple chemistry and
making things like soda,

00:33:18.030 --> 00:33:20.620
and lime, or nitrates.

00:33:20.620 --> 00:33:23.360
But sooner or later,
as our civilization

00:33:23.360 --> 00:33:26.840
encountered during our
history, you reach a threshold.

00:33:26.840 --> 00:33:29.400
You cannot extract the things
you need out of a natural

00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:32.690
environment quickly enough
to support your population.

00:33:32.690 --> 00:33:34.350
So you have to, at
that point, invent

00:33:34.350 --> 00:33:36.890
ways of making
artificial substances,

00:33:36.890 --> 00:33:40.330
making artificial soda like we
worked out in the early 1800s,

00:33:40.330 --> 00:33:42.403
or making artificial
nitrates like we worked out

00:33:42.403 --> 00:33:45.250
in the early 1900s to make
artificial fertilizer,

00:33:45.250 --> 00:33:47.270
and explosives, and gunpowder.

00:33:47.270 --> 00:33:52.020
And that single chemical
reaction of the Haber process

00:33:52.020 --> 00:33:55.210
makes this foul-smelling
compound, ammonia,

00:33:55.210 --> 00:33:58.170
which is responsible for feeding
1/3 of the world's population

00:33:58.170 --> 00:33:58.670
today.

00:33:58.670 --> 00:34:00.900
It's that single
chemical step on which

00:34:00.900 --> 00:34:04.840
I talk about in the
advanced chemistry chapter.

00:34:04.840 --> 00:34:07.040
But I also talk about
the curious chemistry,

00:34:07.040 --> 00:34:10.059
the light-responsive
chemistry of silver.

00:34:10.059 --> 00:34:12.600
And what I'm about to show you
is the most narcissistic slide

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:15.070
I've got in the entire
stack, because I

00:34:15.070 --> 00:34:18.620
wanted even the author's mug
shot on the back of the book

00:34:18.620 --> 00:34:20.820
to remain true to the
premise of the knowledge.

00:34:20.820 --> 00:34:25.020
I wanted to make a photo
from scratch by myself.

00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:27.500
So I went down to
Lacock Abbey in England

00:34:27.500 --> 00:34:29.101
where photography was invented.

00:34:29.101 --> 00:34:30.600
The very first
photographic negative

00:34:30.600 --> 00:34:33.630
was created in the
1830s and 1840s.

00:34:33.630 --> 00:34:36.040
And I worked with
a historian there

00:34:36.040 --> 00:34:39.230
to mix together the
very simple chemistry,

00:34:39.230 --> 00:34:41.850
douse it onto a plate
of glass, load that

00:34:41.850 --> 00:34:45.929
into a primitive single lens
camera, and took this portrait.

00:34:45.929 --> 00:34:49.770
And believe me, this
took all day to get.

00:34:49.770 --> 00:34:51.090
Now, this isn't a snapshot.

00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:53.670
That's a 16 second exposure.

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:55.750
And I would challenge
any one of you

00:34:55.750 --> 00:35:00.180
to sit absolutely dead
still, not allow your head

00:35:00.180 --> 00:35:01.810
to twitch or move
in the slightest,

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:05.526
or your facial muscles to
relax at all for 16 seconds

00:35:05.526 --> 00:35:07.150
to get a picture,
because if you don't,

00:35:07.150 --> 00:35:09.835
if you move in the slightest,
your entire head blurs

00:35:09.835 --> 00:35:12.450
into this ghostly apparition.

00:35:12.450 --> 00:35:14.082
So that's why you
can't smile naturally

00:35:14.082 --> 00:35:15.582
in these simple
photographs, and you

00:35:15.582 --> 00:35:19.080
have to hold this almost
sneery, to be fair, but kind

00:35:19.080 --> 00:35:21.690
of neutral, passive pose.

00:35:21.690 --> 00:35:24.500
And what you can't
see is that behind me,

00:35:24.500 --> 00:35:28.220
there's a raw [? tie-in ?]
stand with a skull clamp locked

00:35:28.220 --> 00:35:31.910
into the back of my head to
hold it absolutely still.

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:34.609
