book and you have access

00:46:23.300 --> 00:46:24.900
to the instrument inside it.

00:46:24.900 --> 00:46:27.640
And actually, acid free paper
is a pretty good storage medium.

00:46:27.640 --> 00:46:30.055
It does last pretty well.

00:46:30.055 --> 00:46:32.990
But I guess if you really
want to take this seriously,

00:46:32.990 --> 00:46:36.030
you would get some enormous
granite slabs and laser engrave

00:46:36.030 --> 00:46:37.910
them with everything
you need to know,

00:46:37.910 --> 00:46:40.250
or at least enough information
that you could bootstrap

00:46:40.250 --> 00:46:42.704
yourself to the next level
to then read a much denser

00:46:42.704 --> 00:46:45.120
store of information, and then
maybe use that to bootstrap

00:46:45.120 --> 00:46:46.310
yourself to the next level.

00:46:46.310 --> 00:46:47.893
And what I'm basically
describing here

00:46:47.893 --> 00:46:50.210
is Asimov's
foundation series, but

00:46:50.210 --> 00:46:51.580
on a post-apocalyptic world.

00:46:51.580 --> 00:46:53.600
AUDIENCE: So I have
one question, as well.

00:46:53.600 --> 00:46:56.620
So what if the survivors
are actually in China,

00:46:56.620 --> 00:46:59.250
and they don't speak English?

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:01.501
LEWIS DARTNELL:
We're translating it.

00:47:01.501 --> 00:47:02.000
BORIS: OK.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.436
LEWIS DARTNELL: For
your flippant answer.

00:47:04.436 --> 00:47:05.939
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:05.939 --> 00:47:06.480
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:47:06.480 --> 00:47:07.790
Thanks for this.

00:47:07.790 --> 00:47:11.690
So of course, the
post-apocalyptic world

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:14.950
is a big topic in
fiction across all media.

00:47:14.950 --> 00:47:18.284
I'm curious if, a, you think
there's any examples out

00:47:18.284 --> 00:47:20.950
there where you think, wow, they
do a really good job with this.

00:47:20.950 --> 00:47:23.756
And also, b, whether you think
anyone, as far as you know,

00:47:23.756 --> 00:47:25.390
is using your book
as a resource to try

00:47:25.390 --> 00:47:30.220
to do a good job of
figuring out this world.

00:47:30.220 --> 00:47:33.872
LEWIS DARTNELL: I don't know
about the second question.

00:47:33.872 --> 00:47:35.580
I get a bunch of emails
a day from people

00:47:35.580 --> 00:47:36.900
that have read the book, and
found it very interesting

00:47:36.900 --> 00:47:39.090
and saying how they were trying
out some of the experiments,

00:47:39.090 --> 00:47:41.150
and things in their
back garden, or building

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:44.750
a gasifier stove with their
kids before a camping trip.

00:47:44.750 --> 00:47:47.120
I don't know if anyone's
trying to rebuild

00:47:47.120 --> 00:47:50.600
their own society on a
desert island using the book.

00:47:50.600 --> 00:47:54.050
So I think most post-apocalyptic
films do a bad job.

00:47:54.050 --> 00:47:56.360
And it's mostly lone
heroes running around

00:47:56.360 --> 00:47:59.430
in leather, which is perhaps, a
little bit too tight and doing

00:47:59.430 --> 00:48:01.140
the Mad Max vibe.

00:48:01.140 --> 00:48:03.580
And clearly, that's
for dramatic tension.

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:06.140
It's more exciting to look at
people running around shooting

00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:09.230
each other for film than a
peaceful community trying

00:48:09.230 --> 00:48:13.360
to build a windmill out
of recycled car parts.

00:48:13.360 --> 00:48:16.250
And books are always
much more nuanced

00:48:16.250 --> 00:48:18.590
in approaching complex issues.

00:48:18.590 --> 00:48:22.120
And again, if you
go under Prepare,

00:48:22.120 --> 00:48:24.350
that tab on the
website under Read,

00:48:24.350 --> 00:48:26.840
there's a list of
the best books which

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:28.467
have approached these ideas.

00:48:28.467 --> 00:48:30.550
So things like "Robinson
Crusoe," or "Swiss Family

00:48:30.550 --> 00:48:32.900
Robinson" deal with this.

00:48:32.900 --> 00:48:34.550
There's a more recent
book by Andy Weir

00:48:34.550 --> 00:48:38.640
called "The Martian," which
is basically a Robinson Crusoe

00:48:38.640 --> 00:48:41.350
meets MacGyver marooned
on Mars and has

00:48:41.350 --> 00:48:44.040
to work at how to not die and
start bootstrapping himself up

00:48:44.040 --> 00:48:45.250
before the rescue mission.

00:48:45.250 --> 00:48:46.675
That is an incredibly good book.

00:48:46.675 --> 00:48:49.971
I did very much
enjoy "The Martian."

00:48:49.971 --> 00:48:52.012
There's a much earlier
book by Jules Verne called

00:48:52.012 --> 00:48:54.586
"The Mysterious
Island," which does

00:48:54.586 --> 00:48:56.835
a really good job of describing
the actual information

00:48:56.835 --> 00:48:58.690
and detail you
would need in a way

00:48:58.690 --> 00:49:00.520
that "Swiss Family
Robinson" brushed over.

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:03.060
And it goes through how to
make different materials

00:49:03.060 --> 00:49:04.570
and the substances for yourself.

00:49:04.570 --> 00:49:08.630
So have a read at that, as well.

00:49:08.630 --> 00:49:10.200
AUDIENCE: One quick
question for you.

00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:13.559
If you did find yourself in
this post-apocalyptic world,

00:49:13.559 --> 00:49:15.350
and let's say you were
back home in the UK,

00:49:15.350 --> 00:49:18.580
or maybe you were in North
America, while there's still

00:49:18.580 --> 00:49:21.260
some transportation
that you could use,

00:49:21.260 --> 00:49:26.891
where would you go to settle
down and start a new world?

00:49:26.891 --> 00:49:28.390
LEWIS DARTNELL: I'm
not sure there's

00:49:28.390 --> 00:49:30.015
any particular place
on the planet that

00:49:30.015 --> 00:49:33.010
would be ideally suited
compared to anywhere else.

00:49:33.010 --> 00:49:35.450
Obviously, don't start trying
to rebuild civilization just

00:49:35.450 --> 00:49:37.479
outside Las Vegas in
the middle of a desert.

00:49:37.479 --> 00:49:39.770
Don't start trying to rebuild
society inside the Arctic

00:49:39.770 --> 00:49:40.380
Circle.

00:49:40.380 --> 00:49:42.885
Make things easy for
yourself and go somewhere

00:49:42.885 --> 00:49:44.510
within the temperate
zone of the planet

00:49:44.510 --> 00:49:47.060
where you've got reliable
rainfall, fertile soil,

00:49:47.060 --> 00:49:49.520
a river nearby, for all of
the same historical reasons

00:49:49.520 --> 00:49:51.260
that the early
civilizations began

00:49:51.260 --> 00:49:53.330
in exactly those environments.

00:49:53.330 --> 00:49:55.150
But the one bit of
advice I would give you

00:49:55.150 --> 00:49:57.700
is get out of the cities
as quickly as you can,

00:49:57.700 --> 00:49:59.990
not least for-- and I
don't ever say the zed word

00:49:59.990 --> 00:50:01.042
in the entire book.

00:50:01.042 --> 00:50:03.000
But if a lot of people
have died in the cities,

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:04.208
they become quite unpleasant.

00:50:04.208 --> 00:50:06.880
They smell bad, but they also
become a huge disease risk

00:50:06.880 --> 00:50:07.680
to you.

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:10.520
But in the longer term,
when you think about it,

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:14.200
a city is an absurdly
artificial bubble.

00:50:14.200 --> 00:50:17.059
And imagine trying to live in
a high rise apartment block

00:50:17.059 --> 00:50:19.100
without electricity running
the elevator and all.

00:50:19.100 --> 00:50:21.619
You have to schlep up 20
floors or flights of stairs

00:50:21.619 --> 00:50:22.660
to get to your apartment.

00:50:22.660 --> 00:50:24.368
And every time you
want a drink of water,

00:50:24.368 --> 00:50:27.390
you have to lift up using your
own muscles with a long rope,

00:50:27.390 --> 00:50:30.090
a bucket to get water to you.

00:50:30.090 --> 00:50:32.460
And without water
pressure in the pipes

00:50:32.460 --> 00:50:34.530
delivering that water
or gas pressure,

00:50:34.530 --> 00:50:37.780
you can't really
live in a modern city

00:50:37.780 --> 00:50:40.730
without the life support
system that civilization

00:50:40.730 --> 00:50:41.790
provides for that city.

00:50:41.790 --> 00:50:43.290
So get out of the city.

00:50:43.290 --> 00:50:45.140
Find yourself a
nice, rural spot,

00:50:45.140 --> 00:50:47.120
with an old,
traditional house where

00:50:47.120 --> 00:50:49.630
there are fire places that
you can burn bits of tree

00:50:49.630 --> 00:50:53.250
in to keep yourself warm, and
a nice plot of fertile soil

00:50:53.250 --> 00:50:56.150
that you can start
rebuilding, and the beginnings

00:50:56.150 --> 00:50:57.670
of farming in.

00:50:57.670 --> 00:51:00.050
BORIS: Please join
me in thanking Lewis.

00:51:00.050 --> 00:51:03.100
[APPLAUSE]

